## Phase 11 M2 (Metal occupancy) — 2026-07-19

M1 ran one thread per output row, one thread per attention head, and one thread
per rmsnorm row, so most GPU lanes sat idle every dispatch. M2 parallelizes
within the existing kernels: a simdgroup per matvec row, a simdgroup per query
head splitting positions, and 256 threads per rmsnorm row. No new features, same
one command buffer per token, same no-copy KV.

Machine: Apple M3 Max, 12 P-cores, 48 GB unified memory.
Models: qwen2.5-0.5b Q8_0/Q4_0/F16, 24 blocks.

Kernel designs:

  quant matvec (q8_0/q4_0)  32 lanes compute exact int8 block dots in parallel
                            into threadgroup memory, lane 0 folds the fp32
                            partials in block order. bitwise vs CPU scalar.
  f16 matvec                32 lanes stride the in-dim, combine with simd_sum.
                            reorders the fp32 fold, atol 1e-4 + rtol 1e-4.
  attention                 simdgroup per head, lanes split positions, softmax
                            max/sum via simd_max/simd_sum. weighted-V sums
                            positions in CPU order. within 1e-4.
  rmsnorm                   256 threads per row, per-simdgroup simd_sum then an
                            8-way fold. reorders the sum, within 1e-4.

Bitwise gate (tests/metal_quant_test), GPU vs CPU scalar, memcmp-identical:

  activation quant  rows {1,4} x in {896,4864}                bit-exact
  Q8_0 matvec       out/in {896,4864,151936-lm_head}/{896,4864} bit-exact
  Q4_0 matvec       same shapes                                bit-exact

design (a) keeps the quant matvec bitwise: the integer block dot is order-free,
and lane 0's fp32 accumulation runs in the same block order as the scalar
reference, one fma per block.

Tolerance gates (tests/metal_ops_test, tests/metal_matmul_test), GPU vs CPU:

  rmsnorm    worst max_err 1.192e-06   (gate 1e-4)
  rope       worst max_err 4.427e-05   (gate 1e-4, unchanged kernel)
  attention  worst max_err 1.192e-07   (gate 1e-4)
  f16 matvec worst atol+rtol ratio 0.64, abs max_err 2.67e-04 at in=4864
             (rel ~1e-5, gate atol 1e-4 + rtol 1e-4)

f16 matvec is the one numerics change: M1's per-row fold was bitwise, so its
metal_matmul_test gate held at a bare atol 1e-4. the simd_sum reorder pushes the
in=4864 shapes to 2.67e-4 absolute (rel ~1e-5), so the gate is now atol 1e-4 +
rtol 1e-4. rmsnorm and attention already carried 1e-4 tolerance and stay inside.

End-to-end greedy, --print-ids, 48 tokens, 2 prompts, gpu-layers 24 vs 0:

  F16   both prompts               token-identical
  Q8_0  'The quick brown fox'      diverges at token 30 (M1: 30)
  Q8_0  'Once upon a time'         diverges at token 9  (M1: 37)
  Q4_0  'The quick brown fox'      diverges at token 3  (M1: identical)
  Q4_0  'Once upon a time'         token-identical      (M1: token 5)

F16 stays token-identical despite the reordered rmsnorm/attention/f16 reductions.
Quant near-tie flips move earlier or later per prompt because rmsnorm and
attention now reduce out of the M1 sequential order; the matvec stays bitwise.
this is the documented near-tie behavior, gated by perplexity, not tokens.

Perplexity, WikiText-2 test, Q8_0, 4 chunks:

  gpu-layers 0    PPL 13.382441
  gpu-layers 24   PPL 13.397496   +0.112%   (M1: +0.055%)

within noise, far inside the 1% weight-quant budget. the slightly larger delta
than M1 is the reordered rmsnorm/attention reductions, not a matvec error.

Decode tok/s, 128 tokens, wall(n=129)-wall(n=1), median of 3:

  model  CPU threaded   M1 gpu   M2 gpu   llama.cpp metal
  Q8_0   87.2           26.4     110.2    245.8
  F16    7.9            6.96     24.9     188.3

Q8_0 GPU decode is 4.2x M1 (26.4 -> 110.2) and now clears the CPU threaded
reference (87.2). F16 GPU is 3.6x the old per-layer path and 3.2x CPU F16.

Gap analysis vs llama.cpp 245.8 (Q8_0). per-token GPU command-buffer time
(GPUEndTime-GPUStartTime) is 5.46 ms (Q8_0) and 6.70 ms (F16). wall is 9.07 ms
(Q8_0, 110 tok/s), so ~3.6 ms/token is CPU-side: the 151936x896 lm_head matvec,
token embedding, final rmsnorm, sampling, and the per-token buffer alloc/memcpy.
llama.cpp runs the entire token, lm_head included, in 4.07 ms; our GPU portion
alone (5.46 ms, no lm_head) already exceeds that. the compute is not the wall:
each token issues ~500 serial dispatches (24 layers x ~21 kernels), so the GPU
spends the time on launch latency and the serial dependency chain between
dispatches at m=1, not on math. occupancy is fixed; dispatch count is not.

M3 (ICB replay / dispatch-count reduction) should target, in order: (1) collapse
the ~500 dispatches/token, fusing rmsnorm+quant, bias+rope into the projection
epilogue, and the residual add into the matvec, and encoding the layer loop once
into an indirect command buffer replayed per token instead of re-encoded; (2)
move the lm_head matvec onto the GPU to erase the ~3.6 ms CPU tail; (3) drop the
per-token host buffer alloc/memcpy by keeping x resident on the device across
the token loop.

## Phase 11 M3 (Metal CPU-tail elimination, persistent activations) — 2026-07-19

M2 left the per-token wall split ~5.46 ms GPU (Q8_0) plus ~3.6 ms CPU: the
151936x896 lm_head on CPU, final rmsnorm, token embedding, sampling, and the
per-token MTLBuffer alloc/memcpy. M3 moves the final rmsnorm and lm_head onto
the same per-token command buffer, keeps every activation device-resident
across the token loop, and folds the two residual adds into the matvec
epilogue.

Machine: Apple M3 Max, 12 P-cores, 48 GB unified memory.
Models: qwen2.5-0.5b Q8_0/F16, 24 blocks.

Changes:

  decode_token_full         appends output_norm + lm_head to the layer command
                            buffer, returns the shared logits buffer pointer.
                            the CPU touches only the embedding row in and the
                            logits out. one waitUntilCompleted per token.
  persistent activations    x, normed, q/attn, scores, gate/up and their quant
                            blocks allocate once in setup_offload and reuse
                            every token. no per-token buffer alloc or host copy.
  residual fold             the wo and wdown matvec epilogue writes acc + x[o]
                            rather than acc, dropping the two add_inplace
                            dispatches per layer. fp32 add is commutative in
                            IEEE, so the quant path stays bitwise.

Dispatch count per token (Q8_0):

  M2   22/layer x 24 + 0 tail (lm_head on CPU)   = 528
  M3   20/layer x 24 + 3 tail (rmsnorm+quant+lm) = 483

  the fold removes 2 dispatches/layer; the tail adds 3 on-device dispatches
  that erase the CPU lm_head. F16 runs 16/layer x 24 + 2 tail = 386.

Bitwise gate (tests/metal_quant_test), GPU vs CPU scalar, memcmp-identical:

  activation quant, Q8_0 matvec, Q4_0 matvec, all shapes incl 151936 lm_head:
  bit-exact. the residual fold keeps add_res=0 on the isolated matvec tests,
  and the folded fp32 add is bitwise vs a separate add on the same acc.

New gate (tests/metal_head_test), the on-device final norm + lm_head:

  final rmsnorm GPU vs CPU            max_err 2.384e-07  (gate 1e-4)
  Q8_0 lm_head bitwise on same normed memcmp identical
  Q4_0 lm_head bitwise on same normed memcmp identical
  Q8_0 tail (rmsnorm+lm_head) vs CPU  max_err 0.000e+00  (gate 1e-4)
  F16  tail (rmsnorm+lm_head) vs CPU  max_err 8.583e-06  (gate 1e-3)

Tolerance gates (tests/metal_ops_test, tests/metal_matmul_test) unchanged:

  rmsnorm 1.192e-06, rope 4.427e-05, attention 1.192e-07, f16 matvec ratio 0.64.

End-to-end greedy, --print-ids, 48 tokens, 2 prompts, gpu-layers 24 vs 0:

  F16   both prompts               token-identical
  Q8_0  'The quick brown fox'      diverges at token 31 (M2: 30)
  Q8_0  'Once upon a time'         diverges at token 10 (M2: 9)

F16 stays token-identical through the on-device lm_head. Q8_0 near-tie flips
track the documented rmsnorm/attention reorder, not the matvec, which is
bitwise. gated by perplexity.

Perplexity, WikiText-2 test, Q8_0, 4 chunks:

  gpu-layers 0    PPL 13.382441
  gpu-layers 24   PPL 13.397497   +0.112%   (M2: +0.112%)

identical to M2, far inside the 1% budget. the on-device lm_head adds no
perplexity drift.

Decode tok/s, 128 tokens, wall(n=129)-wall(n=1), median of 3:

  model  CPU threaded   M2 gpu   M3 gpu   llama.cpp metal
  Q8_0   90.1           110.2    134.7    245.8
  F16    8.5            24.9     120.8    188.3

Q8_0 GPU is 1.22x M2 (110.2 -> 134.7). F16 GPU is 4.85x M2 (24.9 -> 120.8): the
F16 lm_head (151936x896 dequant) dominated the M2 CPU tail, so moving it to the
GPU is the whole jump.

Per-token breakdown (DBINFER_METAL_TIMING, steady_clock encode + GPUEndTime -
GPUStartTime, mean over 128 tokens at position 0-128):

  model  encode   gpu      wall     cpu tail
  Q8_0   0.18 ms  6.75 ms  7.35 ms  ~0 (on GPU)
  F16    0.15 ms  7.61 ms  8.23 ms  ~0 (on GPU)

CPU encode is 0.15-0.18 ms/token, ~2% of wall. an indirect command buffer or
encode-once replay would attack that 2% only, so M3 does not implement it: the
measurement does not justify the complexity. the wall is the GPU command-buffer
time, which is the serial dependency chain across ~480 dispatches at m=1, launch
latency dominated. the residual fold removed 48 light dispatches per token with
no measurable wall change, direct evidence that dispatch-count reduction does
not convert to throughput at this scale; the cost is per-dispatch latency over
the heavy matvecs, not the count of light ops.

Gap analysis vs llama.cpp 245.8 (Q8_0). M3 closed the CPU tail (3.6 ms -> 0) and
the per-token alloc/copy (encode now 0.18 ms). the remaining 6.75 ms GPU time is
~480 serial m=1 dispatches. llama.cpp does the token in 4.07 ms with far fewer,
wider dispatches. closing this needs each dispatch to do more work, not fewer
tiny ones: batch the QKV and gate/up projections into single wide matvecs and
run the matvec with simdgroup_matrix tiles so the GPU is compute-bound rather
than launch-bound. that is M4.

M4 should target, in order: (1) simdgroup_matrix matvec/prefill so each dispatch
saturates the GPU and the m=1 chain stops being launch-bound; (2) batch QKV and
gate/up into single dispatches (one input, multiple weights) to cut the heavy
dispatch count where it now matters; (3) GPU speculative verify. skip ICB: the
encode measurement (0.18 ms) does not justify it.
